Hm. The first thing that stuck out to me here was how vague this was. I feel like I'm missing something while reading through it. Passages like this:



It is hypothesized that by stabilizing the differing frequencies between two areas and the brain, an individual is capable of achieving an out-of-body experience (OBE).
附加记录：    



D-2251 appeared in a quasi projected state, having trouble maintaining a stable frequency even after initial stabilization. D-2251 proceeded to have cortical spreading depolarizations and expired midtest due to severe neurological injury
附加记录：    

make me ask questions like . There's also a fuzzyness to the article that extends to visual _and_ scientific descriptions -



using the impulses generated by the neural gear, the individual is capable of entering the space.
附加记录：    



This area is surrounded by black space, with numerous white lights scattered in the distance.
附加记录：    

What impulses? I'm not entirely sure what  but that could mean a whole range of things. I'm guessing a pocket dimension, but I'm really unsure.

+block

–block


I had a hard time grasping what, exactly, the anomaly was. But that's not the heart of the article, it's the character of Chase. Unfortunately, I felt that Chase was a big example of too much telling, not enough showing. Almost immediately, he explains the stakes and his exact headspace, which then evolves mostly predictably from there. But since I don't understand the anomaly, I'm having a hard time getting situated in what he's trying to do, and why it matters. We're also given time with only him and Skyer, but Skyer is not particularly characterised. So the final meeting where the project has been shuttered, I have no idea why this is significant or why most of the characters are reacting as such.

I get the sense that this article was written with the idea first of  grafted on on top of that. I'm not sure if that's the case, but the unfortunate vagueness of the article with respect to what's actually being researched gives me that impression.





